## Assessments and grading ##
This course will challenge you in rewarding ways. We ask that you:

participate in all class meetings on Mondays and Wednesdays;
participate in a weekly active-learning section each Thursday or Friday;
work through short homework assignments after Monday and Wednesday classes;
pass short quizzes (6 take-home quizzes + 2 in-section quizzes) (no midterms);
complete all programming problem sets;
finish and present one final project (no final exam).
Attendance and engagement. Attendance and engagement at all formal class meetings is expected. The more engaged you are in these class meetings, the more quickly you'll conquer the hump between you today and you with the skills to solve problems with computers. Please read our policies for section.

Due dates, your learning, and your health. Each assignment comes with an explicit due date. These are intentionally spaced to maximize your opportunity to learn and retain the material. We ask that you do your best to abide by these deadlines. In other words, we expect students to be responsible for the management of their own time and prioritize their life in such a manner that it facilitates learning this material.

We realize, however, that life is messy and stuff happens.

For homeworks, take-home quizzes, and final project milestones, we will accept submissions during a grace period of one day after the published due date.
Your lowest homework score will be dropped.
Programming problem sets (psets) have two due dates: an early check-in and a final turn-in. Each pset is released on a Thursday and its check-in due date is the following Wednesday. Final turn-ins will be on a subsequent Friday. We will accept final turn-ins during a grace period that extends until the Monday after the published Friday due date. There are no grace periods for the check-ins.
You do not have to ask the course staff for permission to use any grace period, and there is no penalty for using it. However, staff office hours and Ed discussion monitoring peak in the lead-up to the Friday pset due dates. Staff support will be limited on weekends, so please don't get into the habit of relying on the weekend grace periods.

Furthermore, the teaching staff will track and monitor your usage of grace days and missed class meetings. Any “unusual” patterns in your use of grace days or missed classes will trigger the need for a conversation between you and the teaching staff. “Unusual” patterns include: (1) a big spike in your use of grace days; (2) an accelerating accumulation of grace days over several assignments; and (3) a tightly clustered string of missed class meetings.

You too should track your use of grace days. If you find yourself struggling or notice that this tracking indicates that you might be, please contact the instructor as soon as you feel able. You should not wait for us to contact you. We promise that we will reach out to you when we think your performance warrants a conversation, but you may realize something is wrong before we do.

If you've been to the health center and are sick, we will make exceptions to the assignment deadlines. These exceptions should be requested via email (please email Kitty). If you have other circumstances that will take you away from campus for a significant period of time, please come see Kitty significantly before the missed time to discuss how we will deal with the assignments during this period.

Grading for correctness:

Learning to problem solve and code is hard, and we don't expect you to find every error as you start out. That's not to say that you shouldn't attempt to complete everything in our assignments. You should.

Quizzes and homework assignments are always graded for correctness. Quizzes are testing that you've learned some foundational knowledge, which you should have used several times before the quiz. Homework assignments are checks to see that you understood what we discussed in class, and if you don't, you should find a member of the teaching staff and fix your misunderstanding.
Psets 1-4 are not graded for correctness. You will submit your code and a short video in which you explain what your code does. Your submitted script doesn't need to work without errors to get full credit. However, to get full credit, we must see that you were on the right track (i.e., understood completely what you needed to do and simply failed to overcome some difficult-to-diagnose errors in your code). One way to think about this is, "If your teaching assistant can't fairly quickly diagnose your script's last errors, then we don't expect you to find them." Of course, this assumes that your script is easy to understand by another person; we'll talk about how to organize your scripts in class.
Psets 5-6 and the final project are graded for correctness. You'll still be required to submit your code and a short video explaining it. It is possible that we will give you some credit for situations involving truly obscure errors, as long as you demonstrate in the video that you can explain what you're trying to do and we feel that approach makes sense.
Contributions toward your final grade:

grades on quizzes: 51 points
grades on short homework assignments: 15 points
grades on problem sets: 100 points
grades on all parts of the final project: 32 points
participation at section: 20 points
